						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">Dwedit wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">It's okay to spin on the PPU status register to test vblank when the NES is still in its initial boot phase and hasn't warmed up yet.  If you miss one frame at that point, it's no big deal.</div>Well, probably. Except if you somehow manage to write a test loop which keeps hitting the status bug *every* frame.
<br />
<br />Now according to the wiki you'd have to poll the status bit on exactly the right PPU clock for it to be missed, and as far as I can tell the only time a frame is an whole number of CPU cycles long is on odd NTSC frames when the display is enabled. And in any event a 7-cycle BIT/BPL spin loop isn't even close to being a factor in either standards' timing (though if you get a branch penalty the resulting 8-cycle loop might be).
<br />
<br />But then I'm far from certain about any of this and the PAL details seem a bit sketchy so I think I'd rather take my chances with a proper NMI and avoid all polling altogether.</div>

