			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">doynax wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Well, probably. Except if you somehow manage to write a test loop which keeps hitting the status bug *every* frame.</div><br /><br />Not possible unless you intentially wait at least 1 full frame between $2002 polls.  The glitch only happens if you read on a specific PPU cycle, and since the PPU is 3x the speed of the CPU, and there isn't an integer number of CPU cycles per frame, it'd be impossible to hit the bug on two consecutive frames.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Now according to the wiki you'd have to poll the status bit on exactly the right PPU clock for it to be missed, and as far as I can tell the only time a frame is an whole number of CPU cycles long is on odd NTSC frames when the display is enabled.</div>
<br />
<br />1 frame = 262 scanlines
<br />1 scanline = 341 dots (PPU cycles)
<br />1 CPU cycle = 3 dots
<br />
<br />therefore 1 frame = 262*341/3 = 29780  + 2/3 CPU cycles
<br />
<br />1 dot is missing on the pre-render scanline on odd frames and if the PPU is on, so this could be 29780 + 1/3 cycles instead -- however that still isn't a whole number.
<br />
<br />PAL numbers:
<br />
<br />1 frame = 312 scanlines
<br />1 scanline = 341 dots
<br />1 CPU cycle = 3.2 dots
<br />
<br />therefore 1 frame = 312*341/3.2 = 33247 + 1/2 CPU cycles
<br />
<br />Note PAL does not skip that 1 dot on odd frames like NTSC does.</div>

